## Task 6 SMTP: Sending Email

- Purpose: Defines how mail clients and servers exchange emails.
- Port: TCP 25.
- Commands: HELO/EHLO, MAIL FROM, RCPT TO, DATA, . (end message), QUIT.
Example session (telnet):
- Code
HELO client.thm
MAIL FROM: <user@client.thm>
RCPT TO: <strategos@server.thm>
DATA
Subject: Telnet email
Hello. I am using telnet to send you an email!
.
QUIT
- Wireshark analysis: Shows SMTP dialogue step by step.

---

## Task 7 POP3: Receiving Email

- Purpose: Retrieve emails from server to client.
- Port: TCP 110.
- Commands: USER, PASS, STAT, LIST, RETR, DELE, QUIT.
Example session (telnet):
- Code
telnet MACHINE_IP 110
USER strategos
PASS
STAT → 3 messages
LIST → shows sizes
RETR 3 → retrieves message
QUIT
- Observation: POP3 downloads and deletes messages, like checking a mailbox.
- Security note: Traffic (including passwords) visible in Wireshark captures.
- Credentials for practice: Username: linda, Password: Pa$$123.
- Task 8 IMAP: Synchronizing Email
- Purpose: Synchronize emails across multiple devices.
- Port: TCP 143.
- Commands: LOGIN, SELECT, FETCH, MOVE, COPY, LOGOUT.
Example session (telnet):
- Code
telnet MACHINE_IP 143
LOGIN strategos
SELECT inbox
FETCH 3 body[]
LOGOUT
- Observation: IMAP keeps emails on server, synchronizes read/moved/deleted status across clients.
- Wireshark analysis: Shows client commands (red) and long server responses (blue).
Comparison:
- POP3: Downloads/deletes, minimal server storage.
- IMAP: Synchronizes, uses more server storage.

