## Findings

- DNS resolves names to IPs, enabling web and email communication.
- WHOIS provides transparency into domain ownership.
- HTTP/HTTPS enable web browsing, with methods for data exchange.
- FTP is optimized for file transfer, using separate control/data connections.
- SMTP defines structured communication for sending emails.
- POP3 retrieves and deletes emails, while IMAP synchronizes across devices.
- Wireshark reveals hidden metadata and raw protocol exchanges.

## Mitigation / Best Practices

- Use DNSSEC to secure DNS queries.
- Protect WHOIS privacy with registrar services.
- Always prefer HTTPS over HTTP.
- Use SFTP/FTPS instead of plain FTP.
- Configure SMTP with authentication and TLS.
- Avoid plain POP3/IMAP; use encrypted versions (POP3S, IMAPS).
- Monitor protocol traffic with Wireshark for anomalies.

